Fast, efficient service--was in and out in under 5. Prices are pretty average. Always love a solid neighborhood pizza spot!  The famous grandma slice was not available when I came in.  Plain slice: Crust is crisp and flaky on the outside, stretchy on the inside. The cheese and tomato don't stick out flavor-wise...not necessarily a bad thing. It's one of those where all the flavors meld together into one tasty entity. Slightly more herbaceous than the average plain. Well-seasoned.  White slice: See above. Mozzarella comes through very rich and savory. Pillows of super sweet, fluffy ricotta float on top, nicely countering the saltiness below. I hit mine with red pepper flakes to wake things up. Delicious!  Sicilian: Generous melty stretchy cheese and sauce! Tomato sauce is neutral, neither especially tangy nor sweet. Crust has a beautifully oily crisp outside, and an airy stretchy inside.

Beware if you suffer from a food allergy:  I ordered two pies - one for me, and one for my wife. My wife has Celiac Disease, so she can’t eat gluten. We have ordered from Rocco multiple times in the past with no issue, plus the pizza is pretty decent.  I ordered my wife a gluten free pizza with chicken and spinach (a concoction I don’t like at all), and when the pie arrived, they had used breaded chicken as the topping. My wife cannot have the breading on the chicken (plus who puts breaded chicken on pizza?).  In any case, we were a little annoyed, but mistakes happen. I contacted Slice, the app I ordered through, that my gluten free pizza had breaded chicken on it, and therefore isn’t gluten free. I simply wanted my money back for that part of my order, as my wife can’t even eat it.  I was informed by Slice that Rocco said they received no special instructions, and therefore had “no idea” they needed to use breadless chicken. To be clear: THEY HAD NO IDEA THE GLUTEN FREE PIZZA NEEDED GLUTEN FREE TOPPINGS. Because of that, I was not refunded the $25 (gluten free pizza is expensive!), but I was given $10 back as a sort of... sorry, not sorry thing?  Long story short, if you order from them, and if you have any type of allergy, don’t assume the employees are intelligent enough to understand anything. You have to spell it out, like you would a 6-year-old. Otherwise, how on earth would they know the gluten free pizza needs gluten free toppings?  To be clear, I’m not mad at the mistake. Stuff happens. I’m mad at the lack of accountability and responsibility in the mistake which was made. It’s rather unfortunate too, since their pizza is not bad compared to other neighborhood joints.

This is a pizza restaurant with some booth seating, as well as carry-out and phone/web delivery. I've personally had a few different types of pizza, the chicken wings, and some calzone thing. The basic cheese slice, or potentially the pepperoni or margharita are the two slices I would recommend. At $2.25 and $3 a slice, they are not the $1 pizza place you were looking for, but they have about the same quality you would expect. Plenty of red pepper flakes, oregano, and parm cheese in shakers to dress your average slice. Beyond the two slices I recommended, and potentially the rectangular cheese slice, they have some other "specialty slices for $3.75 a slice (I think) which try to achieve more than they actually accomplish. The buffalo chicken pizza has dry chicken pieces and hot sauce squirted on top. The barbecue chicken pizza is the same, the veggie slice is unseasoned sliced veggies and mozz. I haven't been encouraged to try anything else based on my findings. I'll go there for a night craving, but they close at 11pm, so that isn't very convenient either. It's a reasonable place to hang out and get some food, but don't expect authentic, and don't expect to just dart in and out and have a hot slice.
